b'' b'archive-name: x-faq/part2' b'last-modified: b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the xwd client in the x11 distributions can be used to select a window' b'or the background. it produces an xwd-format file of the image of that window.' b'the file can be post-processed into something useful or printed with the xpr' b'client and your local printing mechanism. you can use this command:' b'csh% sleep xwd -root output.xwd b'and then spend seconds or so setting up your screen; the entire current' b'display will be saved into the file output.xwd. note that xwd also has an' b'undocumented (before r5) -id flag for specifying the window id on the' b'command-line. [there are also unofficial patches on export to xwd for' b'specifying the delay and the portion of the screen to capture.]' b'' b'two publicly-available programs which allow interactive definition of' b'arbitrary portions of the display and built-in delays are asnap and xgrabsc.' b'there are several versions of xgrabsc; version available on export b'is the most recent.' b'xsnap includes some asnap features and supersedes it; it also renders' b'xpm output [version unknown]. it is available on export or avahi.inria.fr;' b'see xsnap-pl2.tar.z.' b'a screen-dump and merge/edit program combining features of xwd and xpr' b'is available from vernam.cs.uwm.edu as xdump1.0.tar.z. information:' b'from cfa0 in xprint.export-2.1.tar.z.' b'' b'to post-process the xwd output of some of these tools, you can use xpr,' b'which is part of the x11 distribution. also on several archives are xwd2ps' b'and xtops, which produce encapsulated postscript with trimmings suitable for' b'use in presentations (see export.lcs.mit.edu:contrib/xwd2ps.tar.z and' b'contrib/imagemagick.tar.z). also useful is the pbmplus package on many archive' b'servers; and the xim package contains level color postscript output.' b'' b'the xv program can grab a portion of the x display, manipulate it, and' b'save it in one of the available formats. imagemagick has similar capabilities.' b'' b'also:' b'' b'2.0, an xlib api for postscript and pcl printers; a demo is on ftp.uu.net' b'in vendor/bristol/xprinter.' b'' b'colorsoft offers openprint package includes a screen-' b'capture facility, image-processing, and support for postscript and' b'non-postscript printers.' b'' b"some vendors' implementations of x (e.g. decwindows and openwindows)" b'include session managers or other desktop programs which include "print portion' b'of screen" or "take a snapshot" options. some platforms also have tools which' b'can be used to grab the frame-buffer directly; the sun systems, for example,' b"have a 'screendump' program which produces a sun raster file. some x terminals" b'have local screen-dump utilities to write postscript to a local serial printer.' b'' b"some vendors' implementations of lpr (e.g. sony) include direct" b"support for printing xwd files, but you'll typically need some other package" b'to massage the output into a useful format which you can get to the printer.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'if you need color postscript in particular, you can' b'- grab the screen-image using a program which can produce color' b'postscript, such as xgrabsc and xv' b'- grab the screen-image using xwd and post-process xwd into color ps.' b'you can do this using xwd2ps or the xtops program from the imagemagick' b'distribution. the pbmplus package is also good for this, as is the xim package.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b"this can't be done unless the x server has been extended. consider" b'instead a system-dependent mechanism for, e.g., capturing the frame-buffer.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b"the likeliest program is an incarnation of jef poskanzer's useful++" b'portable bitmap toolkit, which includes a number of programs for converting' b'among various image formats. it includes support for many types of bitmaps,' b'gray-scale images, and full-color images. pbmplus has been updated recently;' b'the most recent version is on export in contrib/pbmplus10dec91.tar.z.' b"another tool is san diego supercomputing center's imtools ('imconv' in" b'particular), which packages the functionality of pbm into a single binary.' b"it's available anonymous ftp from sdsc.edu b'' b"useful for viewing some image-formats is jim frost's xloadimage, a" b'version of which is in the r4 directory contrib/clients/xloadimage; there are' b'later versions available, including contrib/xloadimage.3.03.tar.z on export.' b"graeme gill's updates to an earlier version of xloadimage are also on export;" b'see xli.readme and xli.tar.z.uu; version was released b'' b'can read and display pictures in sun raster, pgm, pbm, ppm, x11 bitmap, tiff,' b'gif and jpeg. it can manipulate on the images: adjust, color, intensity,' b'contrast, aspect ratio, crop). it can save images in all of the aforementioned' b'formats plus postscript. it can grab a portion of the x display, manipulate on' b'it, and save it in one of the available formats. the program was updated b'see the file contrib/xv-2.21.tar.z on export.lcs.mit.edu.' b'' b'conversion and manipulation package, similar to pbmplus. version available' b'via ftp as nl.cs.cmu.edu:/usr/mlm/ftp/fbm.tar.z, uunet.uu.net:pub/fbm.tar.z,' b'and ucsd.edu:graphics/fbm.tar.z.' b'' b'and writes its own image format, displays on an x11 screen, and does some image' b'manipulations. version is available via ftp on expo.lcs.mit.edu as' b'contrib/img_1.3.tar.z, along with large collection of color images.' b'' b'the utah rle toolkit is a conversion and manipulation package similar' b'to pbmplus. available via ftp as cs.utah.edu:pub/urt-*,' b'weedeater.math.yale.edu:pub/urt-*, and freebie.engin.umich.edu:pub/urt-*.' b'' b'xim, the x image manipulator, by philip thompson, does essential' b'interactive displaying, editing, filtering, and converting of images. there is' b'a version in the x11r4 contrib area; but a more recent version (using r4 and' b'motif is available from gis.mit.edu xim reads/writes gif,' b'xwd, xbm, tiff, rle, xim, (writes level eps) and other formats and also has a' b'library and command-line utilities for building your own applications.' b'' b"export's contrib area. it is a collection of utilities to transform and display" b'images on any x server. the tool uses the miff format; filters to and from miff' b'from other popular formats (ppm, tiff, gif, sun raster, etc) are included.' b'' b'xtiff is a tool for viewing a tiff file in an x window. it was written' b'to handle as many different kinds of tiff files as possible while remaining' b'simple, portable and efficient. xtiff illustrates some common problems' b'with building pixmaps and using different visual classes. it is distributed' b"as part of sam leffler's libtiff package and it is also available on" b'xtiff was announced in it includes xlib and xt versions.' b'' b'is available as contrib/vimage-0.9.3.tar.z on export.lcs.mit.edu. the package' b'also includes an imageviewport widget and a filedialog widget. b'' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the solution involves sending an escape sequence to xterm which will' b'cause it to update the property which the window manager relies upon for the' b'string which appears in the window titlebar.' b'a solution is as easy as typing this in an xterm running a shell:' b'echo "esc]2;text^g"' b'where esc is the escape key, text is the string you wish to have displayed,' b'and ^g is a control-g (the bel character).' b'' b'here is a more complicated csh alias which changes the titlebar to' b'the current working directory when you change directories:' b"alias newcd 'cd echo -n esc]2\\;$cwd^g'" b'' b"the digit in these strings indicates to xterm that it should" b'change only the title of the window; to change both the title and the name' b"used in the icon, use the digit instead, and use to change only the" b'icon name.' b'' b'note: another way to do this, which prevents an incorrect display of' b'the local directory if a modified `cd` is used in a subshell, is to wrap the' b'escape sequences into the ps1 prompt itself.' b'' b'note: on an ibm rs/6000 is may be necessary to begin the sequence with' b'a ^v.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the best source of such information is in your r5 sources in the file' b'ctlseqs.ms; a postscript version is in mit/hardcopy/clients/ctlseqs.ps.z.' b'' b"o'reilly's volume the x user's guide, includes an r5 version of the control" b'sequences; the standard volume will be available and a motif version of' b'the book is available now. the current (r4) guide includes an outdated version' b'of the control sequences. b'' b'other good sources of information include the r4 version of that document' b'and also the file in the r4 sources called mit/clients/xterm/ctlseq2.txt, a' b'compilation put together by skip montanaro (ge cr&d) listing the vt100' b'sequences. it dates from r3 but is fairly accurate. a hardcopy version was' b'published in the december xnextevent (the xug newsletter).' b'' b'in a pinch, a vt100 manual will do.' b'' b'[last updated b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'in order to use special characters such as the o-umlaut, you need to' b'"stty pass8" but also to use a charcell iso8859 font, such as' b'xterm*font: \t-*-*-medium-r-normal-*-*-130-*-*-c-*-iso8859-1' b'xterm*boldfont:\t-*-*-bold-r-normal-*-*-130-*-*-c-*-iso8859-1' b'[the family is intentionally unspecified in this example.]' b'' b'in addition, you may want to set this in your shell:' b'setenv lc_ctype iso_8859_1' b'' b'for a given character above you can determine the key to use with' b'the alt modifier by finding the equivalent character below (try using' b"`man ascii`). for example, o-umlaut (v) is alt-v and the section character b"is alt-'." b'' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'you are probably setting the geometry small accidentally. if you give' b'a resource specification like this:' b'xterm*geometry: 80x24' b'then you are asking for all widgets under xterm to have their geometry set to' b'80x24. for the main window, this is ok, as it uses characters for its size.' b"but its popup menus don't; they are in pixels and show up small. to set only" b'the terminal widget to have the specified geometry, name it explicitly:' b'xterm*vt100.geometry: 80x24' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'you could paste it into an xterm after executing the lpr command.' b'manipulating the selection will help; e.g.' b'% xselection primary lpr' b'finds the primary selection and prints it. this command can be placed in a' b'window-manager menu or in shell-scripts. xselection also permits the setting of' b'the selection and other properties. a version is on export.' b'also available is ria.ccs.uwo.ca:pub/xget_selection.tar.z, which can be' b'adapted to do this.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'you can use several environment variables to control how resources are' b'loaded for your xt-based programs xfilesearchpath, xuserfilesearchpath, and' b'xapplresdir. these environment variables control where xt looks for' b'application-defaults files as an application is initializing. xt loads at most' b'one app-defaults file from the path defined in xfilesearchpath and another from' b'the path defined in xuserfilesearchpath.' b'' b'set xfilesearchpath if software is installed on your system in such a' b'way that app-defaults files appear in several different directory hierarchies.' b"suppose, for example, that you are running sun's open windows, and you also" b'have some r4 x applications installed in /usr/lib/x11/app-defaults. you could' b'set a value like this for xfilesearchpath, and it would cause xt to look up' b'app-defaults files in both /usr/lib/x11 and /usr/openwin/lib (or wherever your' b'openwinhome is located):' b'setenv xfilesearchpath /usr/lib/x11/%t/%n:$openwinhome/lib/%t/%n' b'' b'the value of this environment variable is a colon-separated list of pathnames. the pathnames contain replacement characters as follows (see' b'xtresolvepathname()):' b'' b'%n the value of the filename parameter, or the' b"application's class name." b'%t the value of the file "type". in this case, the' b'literal string "app-defaults"' b'%c customization resource (r5 only)' b'%s suffix. none for app-defaults.' b'%l language, locale, and codeset (e.g. "ja_jp.euc")' b'%l language part of %l (e.g. "ja")' b"%t the territory part of the display's language string" b"%c the codeset part of the display's language string" b'' b"let's take apart the example. suppose the application's class name is" b'"myterm". also, suppose open windows is installed in /usr/openwin. (notice the' b'example omits locale-specific lookup.)' b'/usr/lib/x11/%t/%n means /usr/lib/x11/app-defaults/myterm' b'$openwinhome/lib/%t/%n means /usr/openwin/lib/app-defaults/myterm' b'' b'as the application initializes, xt tries to open both of the above' b'app-defaults files, in the order shown. as soon as it finds one, it reads it' b'and uses it, and stops looking for others. the effect of this path is to' b'search first in /usr/lib/x11, then in /usr/openwin.' b'' b"let's consider another example. this time, let's set" b'xuserfilesearchpath so it looks for the file myterm.ad in the current working' b'directory, then for myterm in the directory ~/app-defaults.' b'setenv xuserfilesearchpath ./%n.ad:$home/app-defaults/%n' b'' b'the first path in the list expands to ./myterm.ad. the second expands' b'to $home/app-defaults/myterm. this is a convenient setting for debugging' b'because it follows the imake convention of naming the app-defaults file' b"myterm.ad in the application's source directory, so you can run the application" b'from the directory in which you are working and still have the resources loaded' b'properly. note: when looking for app-default files with xuserfilesearchpath,' b'for some bizarre reason, neither the type nor file suffix is defined so %t and' b'%s are useless.' b'' b"with r5, there's another twist. you may specify a customization" b'resource value. for example, you might run the "myterm" application like this:' b'myterm -xrm "*customization: -color"' b'' b'if one of your pathname specifications had the value' b'"/usr/lib/x11/%t/%n%c" then the expanded pathname would be' b'"/usr/lib/x11/app-defaults/myterm-color" because the %c substitution character' b'takes on the value of the customization resource.' b'' b'the default xfilesearchpath, compiled into xt, is:' b'/usr/lib/x11/%l/%t/%n%c:\\ (r5)' b'/usr/lib/x11/%l/%t/%n%c:\\ (r5)' b'/usr/lib/x11/%t/%n%c:\\ (r5)' b'/usr/lib/x11/%l/%t/%n:\\' b'/usr/lib/x11/%l/%t/%n:\\' b'/usr/lib/x11/%t/%n' b'' b'(note: some sites replace /usr/lib/x11 with a projectroot in' b'this batch of default settings.)' b'' b'the default xuserfilesearchpath, also compiled into xt, is' b'<root/%l/%n%c:\\ (r5)' b'<root/%l/%n%c:\\ (r5)' b'<root/%n%c:\\ (r5)' b'<root/%l/%n:\\' b'<root/%l/%n:\\' b'<root/%n:' b'' b"<root is either the value of xapplresdir or the user's home directory" b'if xapplresdir is not set. if you set xuserfilesearchpath to some value other' b'than the default, xt ignores xapplresdir altogether.' b'' b'notice that the quick and dirty way of making your application find' b'your app-defaults file in your current working directory is to set xapplresdir' b'to a single dot. in r3, all this machinery worked differently; for r3' b'compatibilty, many people set their xapplresdir value to a dot followed' b'by a slash.' b'' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b"the answer lies in changing xdm's xrdb resource in the xdm-config file to run a" b'program to change the background before loading the resources; for example,' b'your /usr/lib/x11/xdm/xdm-config file may add the line' b'displaymanager.0.authorize: false' b'to permit unrestricted access to the display before log-in (beware!) and also' b'displaymanager*xrdb:\t/usr/lib/x11/xdm/new.xrdb' b'where that file does something (for all connections) along the lines of:' b'#!/bin/sh' b'#comes in with arguments: -display -load /usr/lib/x11/xdm/xresources' b'/usr/bin/x11/xsetroot -display -bitmap /usr/lib/x11/xdm/new.bitmap' b'/usr/bin/x11/xrdb b'substitute xloadimage or xv for xsetroot, to taste. note that this is a' b'general hack that can be used to invoke a console window or any other client.' b'' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b"when xdm runs your .xsession it doesn't source your .cshrc or .login" b'files. you can set the path explicitly as you normally could for any sh script;' b'or you can place all environment-setting statements in a separate file and' b'source it from both the .xsession file and your shell configuration file; or,' b'if you set your path in your .cshrc file, the normal place, you can make your' b'.xsession have path set simply by making it a csh script, i.e. by starting' b'your .xsession file off with "#!/bin/csh".' b"if this doesn't work, also try starting off with:" b'#!/bin/sh' b'# reset path:' b"path=`csh -c 'echo $path'` export path" b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'there are several ways to avoid having to do a "setenv display b'whenever you log in to another networked unix machine running x.' b'one solution is to use the clients/xrsh on the r5 contrib tape. it' b'includes xrsh, a script to start an x application on remote machine, and' b'xrlogin, a script to start a local xterm running rlogin to a remote machine.' b'a more recent version is on export in xrsh-5.4.shar.' b'one solution is to use the xrlogin program from der mouse' b'132.206.1.1, in x/xrlogin.c and x/xrlogind.c. the program packages up $term and' b'$display into a single string, which is stuffed into $term. rlogin then' b'propagates $term normally; your .cshrc on the remote machine should contain' b'eval `xrlogind`' b'where xrlogind is a program that checks $term and if it is of the special' b'format it recognizes, unpacks it and spits out setenv and unsetenv commands to' b'recreate the environment variables. b'' b'in addition, if all you need to do is start a remote x process on' b'another host, and you find' b'rsh <host -n /usr/bin/x11/xterm -display $display' b'too simple (display must have your real hostname), then this version of xrsh' b'can be used to start up remote x processes. the equivalent usage would be' b'xrsh <host xterm' b'' b'#! /bin/sh' b'# start an x11 process on another host' b'# date: dec gmt' b'#' b'# an improved version:' b'#' b"# but they put the rcmd in ()'s which left zombies again. this" b'# script combines the best of both.' b'' b'case in' b'[01]) echo "usage: host x-cmd [args...]";;' b'*)' b'case $shell in' b'*csh*) host="$1"; shift' b'xhost "$host" /dev/null' b'rsh "$host" -n b'"setenv term xterm; setenv display `hostname`:0; b'exec </dev/null /dev/null" b';;' b'*sh)' b'host="$1"; shift' b'xhost "$host" /dev/null' b'rsh "$host" -n b'"term=xterm export term; b'display=`hostname`:0 export display; b'ld_library_path=/usr/x11/lib export ld_library_path; b'path=\\$path:/usr/x11/bin:/usr/bin/x11:/usr/local/bin; b'export path; b'exec /dev/null /dev/null b';;' b'esac' b';;' b'esac' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'one way is to use the "bitmap" client or some other bitmap-editor (e.g.' b"sun's icon-editor tool, post-processed with pbmplus) to design the individual" b'characters and then to do some large amount of post-processing to concatenate' b"them into the bdf format. see ollie jones's article in the november x" b'journal for more information.' b'the r3 contrib/ area (in fonts/utils/ and in clients/xtroff) contained' b'a number of useful utilities, including some to convert between bdf font format' b'and a simple character format which can be edited with any text editor.' b'an easier way is to use the "xfed" client to modify an existing font; a' b'version is on the r4 or r5 x11r5 contrib tape in contrib/clients/xfed. xfed is' b'available for anonymous ftp on ftp.informatik.uni-dortmund.de b'possibly as file /pub/windows/x/diverse-x11-sourcen/xfed.tar.z. it can produce' b'bdf-format fonts which can be compiled for a variety of x servers.' b'the xfedor client from group bull permits creation of bitmaps, cursors,' b'xpm1 pixmaps, and fonts. binaries for common machines are on avahi.inria.fr in' b'/pub; in addition, the sources (an old xlib implementation) have been placed' b'[5/91] in export:/contrib.' b'if you are a metafont user you can use "mftobdf" from the seetex' b'distribution to convert pk, gf, and pxl fonts to bdf format; the distribution' b'is on ftp.cs.colorado.edu and on export.lcs.mit.edu.' b'the gnu package fontutils-0.4.tar.z on prep.ai.mit.edu includes xbfe,' b'a font editor, and a number of utilities for massaging font formats.' b"the o'reilly x resource issue contains an article on using these" b'tools to modify a font.' b"fonts can be resized with hiroto kagotani's bdfresize; a new version is" b'in ftp.cs.titech.ac.jp:/x11/contrib.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b"after you have built the font using your system's font-compiler," b"installed it in some directory, and run `mkfontdir` or your system's equivalent" b'(e.g. bldfamily for openwindows) in that directory, be sure to use `xset +fp' b"$dir` to add that full path-name to the server's font-path, *or* if the" b'directory is already in the path, use `xset fp rehash` so that the new fonts in' b"that directory are actually found; it is this last step that you're probably" b'leaving out. (you can also use `xset q` to make sure that that directory is in' b'the path.)' b'sometimes your "xset +fp $dir" command fails with a badvalue error:' b'x error of failed request:badvalue' b'(integer parameter out of range for operation)' b'major opcode of failed request: (x_setfontpath)' b'' b'this means the x server cannot find or read your font directory, or' b'that your directory does not look like a font directory to the server. (the' b'mention of an "integer parameter" in the message is spurious.)' b'' b"-- is the font directory you're specifying readable from the server's file" b"system? remember, it's the server, not the client, which interprets your" b'font directory. trouble in this area is especially likely when you issue an' b'xset command with shell metacharacters in it (e.g. "xset +fp ~/myfonts") and' b'the server is an x terminal or managed by xdm.' b'' b"-- is the directory really a font directory? if you're running an mit server" b'(or most varieties of vendor servers) look in the directory for the file' b'"fonts.dir". if you can\'t find that file, run mkfontdir(1). (if you\'re' b'running openwindows, look for the file "families.list". if you can\'t find' b'it, run bldfamily(1).)' b'' b"-- if you're in a site where some people run x11rn servers and others run a" b'proprietary server with nonstandard font formats (openwindows, for' b"example), make sure the font directory is right for the server you're using." b"hint: if the directory contains .pcf and/or .snf files, it won't work for" b"open windows. if the directory contains .ff and/or .fb files, it won't work" b'for x11rn.' b'' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'a tool called "snftobdf is part of the bdftools package, which is' b'available from export.lcs.mit.edu:contrib/bdftools.tar.z and from' b'crl.nmsu.edu:pub/misc/bdftools.tar.z. b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b"der mouse's getbdf is one solution; it connects to a server and" b'produces a .bdf file for any font the server is willing to let it. it can be' b'used as an anything-to-bdf converter, but requires access to a server that can' b'understand the font file, thus is both more and less powerful than other tools' b'such as snftobdf. getbdf is on in x/getbdf.c or available via mail' b'in addition, the r5 program "fstobdf" can produce bdf for any font that' b'the r5 server has access to.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b"the decwindows fonts typically don't exist on a non-dec installation," b'but rewrite rules can be used to alias fonts used by decwindows applications to' b'standard mit fonts of similar characteristics and size. pick up the file' b'contrib/decwindows_on_x11r4_font.aliases from export.lcs.mit.edu; this file is' b'for a standard mit r4 server. it can also serve as a starting point for' b'creating a similar aliases file for the open windows server or other servers' b'which do not use the mit font scheme.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the format of fonts preferred by dec\'s x server is the ".pcf" format.' b"you can produce this compiled format from the .bdf format by using dec's dxfc" b'font-compiler. note that the dec servers can also use raw .bdf fonts, with a' b'performance hit.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'i want to be able to do something like this:' b'xclock*backgroundpixmap: /usr/include/x11/bitmaps/rootweave' b'' b"you can't do this. the backgroundpixmap resource is a pixmap of the" b'same depth as the screen, not a bitmap (which is a pixmap of depth because' b'of this, writing a generic string to pixmap converter is impossible, since' b'there is no accepted convention for a file format for pixmaps. therefore,' b'neither the x toolkit or the athena widget set define a string to pixmap' b'converter, because there is no converter you cannot specify this value as a' b'resource. the athena widget set does define a string to bitmap converter for' b'use in many of its widgets, however.' b'' b'however:' b'a specific converter which encapsulates much of the functionality of' b'the xloadimage package by jim frost was posted by sebastian wangnick' b'image formats as a pixmap.' b'' b'the leading general-purpose format for pixmaps is the xpm format used' b'by groupe bull in several of its programs, including the gwm window manager, by' b'at&t in its olpixmap editor, and by ics in its interface builder. xpm' b'distribution, available on export as contrib/xpm.tar.z, includes read/write' b'routines which can easily be adapted to converters by new widgets which want to' b'allow specification of pixmap resources in the above manner. see information' b'on the xpm-talk mailing list above. xpm 3.0f was announced in and is' b'available from export.lcs.mit.edu and avahi.inria.fr; an older version is on' b'the r5 contrib tape. [a set of xpm icons collected by anthony thyssen' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'you probably have an extra space after the specification of the first' b'item, like this:' b'basic*text.translations: #override b'ctrl<keya: beginning-of-line() \\n\\' b'ctrl<keye: end-of-line()' b'^ extra space' b'the newline after that space is ending the translation definition.' b'[thanks to timothy j. horton, b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'one solution is xchron, in volume of comp.sources.x, which can show' b'the time for timezones other than the local one.' b'alternatively, you can probably set the timezone in the shell from' b'which you invoke the xclock or oclock, or use a script similar to this:' b'#!/bin/sh' b'tz=pst8pdt xclock -name "san_luis_obispo_ca" /dev/null b'tz=est5edt xclock -name "king_of_prussia_pa" /dev/null b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the xmh mail-reader requires the rand mh mail/message handling system,' b'which is not part of the unix software distribution for many machines. a list' b'of various ftp, uucp, e-mail and us-mail sites for both xmh and mh is given in' b'the monthly mh faq; one source is ics.uci.edu in the file pub/mh/mh-6.7.tar.z.' b'if you do not receive the comp.mail.mh newsgroup or the mh-users mailing list,' b'you can request a copy of the faq, which also includes a section on xmh,' b'"send usenet/news.answers/mh-faq".' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'after a seemingly random amount of time after the x server has been started, no' b'other clients are able to connect to it.' b'' b'the default cron cleanup jobs supplied by sun (for at least)' b'delete "old" (unreferenced) files from /tmp including /tmp/.x11-unix, which' b'contains the socket descriptor used by x. the solution is to add -type s" to' b'the find exclusion in the cron job.' b'[10/90]' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'the r5 sample server implementation works only on color screens, sorry.' b'' b'----------------------------------------------------------------------' b'' b'many users wants the num lock key to light the num lock led and have the' b'appropriate effect on the numeric keypad. the xsun server as distributed by mit' b"doesn't do this but there are two different patches available." b'' b'the first patch is written by jonathan lemon and fixes the num lock related' b'problems. it is available from export.lcs.mit.edu in the file' b'contrib/xsun-r5.numlock_patch.z b'' b'the second is written by martin forssen and fixes the num lock and compose keys' b'and adds support for the different national keyboard layouts for type-4 and' b'type-5 keyboards. this patch is available from export.lcs.mit.edu in' b'' b